  My First 72 Hours with a 3D Printer
From "What the hell do I do with this" to Robotics and AI
Three days ago, I bought my first 3D printer.
My original goal was simple: learn how to design/source and print a few useful objects.
I had no idea that decision would immediately send me down one of the deepest rabbit holes I've ever experienced.
________________________________________
Day 1: The Magic of Turning Ideas into Reality
The first successful print felt like science fiction.
Creating something in software and then watching it materialize layer by layer on my desk was incredibly satisfying. Almost immediately, I found myself asking:
•	What else can I build?
•	How far can I push this?
•	What happens if the printed object can move?
That last question changed everything.
________________________________________
Day 2: Discovering Robotics and Actuation
I started researching how physical objects move.
That led me into:
•	Servo motors
•	Stepper motors
•	Gear trains
•	Rack and Pinion systems
•	Linkages and mechanisms
•	CAD design in Fusion 360
What started as "printing things" quickly became "building machines."
I've spent hours sketching concepts, designing parts, and learning how motion can be translated through gears, belts, and mechanical assemblies.
Every answer seemed to generate five new questions.
________________________________________
Day 3: The AI Integration Rabbit Hole
Naturally, my brain started asking:
What if these machines could make decisions?
That question led me into:
•	Computer vision
•	Machine learning
•	Edge AI
•	Sensor integration
•	Autonomous systems
•	AI-assisted robotics
Now I'm exploring projects that combine:
3D Printing
     +
Mechanical Design
     +
Electronics
     +
Actuation
     +
Artificial Intelligence
The possibilities feel almost limitless.
________________________________________
Current Projects and Ideas
Some concepts I'm currently exploring:
•	Smart cat door systems
•	Automated enclosures
•	AI-powered pet monitoring
•	Servo-driven mechanisms
•	Custom robotic assemblies
•	Sensor-integrated devices
Many of these ideas are probably overly ambitious for someone who has owned a 3D printer for only a few days.
That isn't stopping me.
________________________________________
What I've Learned So Far
The biggest realization has been that a 3D printer isn't just a tool.
It's a gateway.
A gateway into:
•	Engineering
•	Product design
•	Robotics
•	Manufacturing
•	Embedded systems
•	Artificial intelligence
Every project teaches multiple disciplines at once.
________________________________________
Looking Ahead
This repository will serve as a journal of that journey.
I'll be documenting:
•	CAD models
•	Design iterations
•	Robotics experiments
•	Actuation systems
•	AI integrations
•	Successes and failures
Right now, I know just enough to realize how much I don't know.
And honestly, that's the most exciting part.
